Operating System (OS):
The device explicitly states it uses Windows 7 as its operating system (14-1).
Diagnostic software used is proprietary and maintained by SJM trained technicians exclusively (14-2 notes).
System and Application Hardening (SAHD) (Section 15):
The device employs hardening measures. It uses application control via McAfee AppControl, which uses a whitelist to block anything not on it, helping protect against malware, viruses, and other threats (15-1 notes, referencing Section 4).
The file system supports the implementation of file-level access controls (NTFS) for MS Windows platforms (15-4).
Accounts and shared resources not required for the device's intended use are disabled or deleted (15-5, 15-6).
Communication ports and services not required for the intended use are closed/disabled (15-7, 15-8, 15-9).
The device cannot boot from uncontrolled or removable media due to BIOS settings (15-10 and notes).
Software not authorized by the device manufacturer cannot be installed without tools or if not on the supported whitelist (15-11 and notes).
Antivirus (Anti-malware):
Malware Detection/Protection (MLDP) (Section 10):
The device does not directly support the use of anti-malware software or have the user independently re-configure settings, nor does it provide malware detection notifications in the UI (10-1, 10-1.1, 10-1.2).
Manufacturer-authorized persons are typically required for system repairs post-malware detection (10-1.3).
The device owner cannot install or update antivirus software (10-2).
The manufacturer's installed anti-virus software definitions cannot be updated by the owner/operator (10-3).
However, the system primarily relies on whitelisting (via McAfee AppControl, as mentioned in Section 4 and 10-1 notes) to help prevent malware by not allowing unauthorized execution.
Patching:
Cyber Security Product Upgrades (CSUP) (Section 5):
Relevant OS and device security patches can be applied to the device as they become available (5-1).
Software updates are provided every 9-12 months and involve validation for functional software updates in conjunction with device OS and related patches (5-1 notes).
Security patches or other software cannot be installed remotely (5-1.1). Installation is typically done by on-site or remote service staff.

OPW: ID 2006 SEQ Circinus Bolt Navigation System
ASA Assigned: William Lee / Kelly Nicholson / Ronald Cyr
Comments:
Anthony Damiano , 11/1/2023 4:16:42 PM:  Good afternoon:
As foundation, the device is a standalone iOS device (7th generation iPod touch).  It is provisioned at the factory via an MDM server (Jamf) such that it only has the Bolt Navigation program on it.  There is no access to any other programs on the device.  The Bolt program is native on the device and requires no connectivity to function.  The only time that it could theoretically be required to connect to the internet is if / when a program update is available.  In this case, notice will be sent to the customer with specific instructions to connect to a secure internet connection.  (Note that this connection can be outside of the hospital.)  As soon as the device connects to the interned it will receive the update via the MDM server.  It can then be disconnected again from the internet.
Having said this, the current proposal is for a two-month trial of the system.  In this two months there will not be any updates and therefor no connectivity is required.  (We anticipate that updates will be on an annual basis in the future.)
Please let me know if you need any additional information.
___________________________________________________________

Lenczewski, Michael - PHX , 5/12/2020 10:47:28 AM: Per Jason: While I do not have access to ED patient volumes.   Based on the Physician ordering patterns and the Radiology study volumes at the SM ED I can conjecture that the patient volumes only averages about 100 patients a day so 33 per day would be very high.   At the same time 33 per month seems low to me.  That would only be about 1.5% of their volumes.  I would think a realistic number would be about 10 to 12 per day.
The study size of 149 mb is a number I came calculated by using the average US image size for those currently being stored from other US machines and the proposed usage by the physician.  This could change significantly if they store more than 1 3 second cine clip as Dr Bennett told us would be done.  Unfortunately as this is going to be controlled by the ED physicians and not internally in Radiology I have no better information on what to expect.

Nick I filled out the form as best as I could but there are some fields that are still missing information please be sure to review and add the missing information.

Will the device be configured to de-identify private data? (MDS2 states it has this capability)

There are a number of identified security concerns with this device, but if the data is de-identified and/or not retained on the device then some of the issues do not need to be documented as exceptions.
Thanks!
Brett Larsen

Governance, Risk and Compliance
